T1  - Trade, accumulation, and uneven development
AU  - Krugman, Paul
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 8
IS  - 2
SP  - 149
EP  - 161
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(81)90026-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387881900262
AB  - This paper develops a two-country model of capital accumulation and growth where the industrial sector exhibits increasing returns to scale. It shows that ‘uneven development’ is a necessary outcome in such a model: an initial discrepancy in capital-labor ratios between the two countries will cumulate over time, leading to the division of the world into a capital-rich, industrial region and capital-poor, agricultural region. Which region takes on which role depends on ‘primative accumulation’; that is, on which region starts with more capital. If capital is mobile internationally, the model can given rise to a two-stage pattern of development — a first stage where trade is the engine of growth in the leading country, and a second in which foreign investment takes on that role — which is reminiscent of the Hobson-Lenin theory of imperialism.
ER  - 

